  "prompt": "How do colleges look at community college transcript (along with the high school transcript) for undergraduates?",
  "response": "Colleges generally view community college transcripts positively when evaluating undergraduate transfer applications. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Transfer Credits\n- Most colleges have specific transfer credit policies\n- Credits are typically evaluated for course equivalency and applicability to degree requirements\n- Good grades (usually C or better) are more likely to transfer\n\n2. Academic Performance\n- Colleges look at overall GPA from community college\n- Consistent or improved academic performance is viewed favorably\n- Challenging coursework and successful completion are important\n\n3. Articulation Agreements\n- Many universities have formal agreements with community colleges\n- These agreements outline which credits will transfer automatically\n- Some have guaranteed transfer paths for specific programs\n\n4. Admission Advantages\n- Community college credits can demonstrate academic capability\n- Shows motivation and ability to succeed in college-level courses\n- Can help students who may not have strong high school academic records\n\n5. Potential Scholarship Opportunities\n- Some schools offer specific transfer scholarships\n- Strong community college performance can enhance scholarship potential\n\n6. Holistic Review\n- Transcripts are typically reviewed in context with other application materials\n- Extracurricular activities, essays, and recommendations also matter\n\n7. Pathway Programs\n- Some universities have specific transfer pathways for community college students\n- These programs can streamline the transfer process\n\nRecommendations: Research specific transfer policies for target universities.",
